data.title: Hagerty reports strong 2025 results: Revenue up 17% to $1.46B, Net Income jumps 91%. 371K new members added.
data.description: In 2025, the total revenue saw a significant rise of 17% to reach $1,456 million, while the written premium increased by 14% to $1,194 million. A record number of 371,000 new members were added during the year. Marketplace revenue also experienced a substantial increase of 119% to $119 million. Income before taxes showed a notable growth of 49% amounting to $139 million. Net income saw the most substantial increase, rising by 91% compared to the previous year.

data.title: Krispy Kreme's Q4 2025: Revenue $392.4M with Organic Rev down 3.9% & Net Loss $29.1M; Adjusted EBITDA $55.6M; Operating Cash $45.0M.
data.description: Krispy Kreme, Inc. (NASDAQ: DNUT) disclosed its financial outcomes for the last quarter and full year concluded on December 28, 2025. In comparison to Q4 2024, the company achieved a net revenue of $392.4 million, although there was a fall of 3.9% in organic revenue due to the deliberate shutdown of unproductive outlets. Krispy Kreme also reported a GAAP net loss of $29.1 million, with an adjusted EBITDA of $55.6 million. Additionally, the company generated $45.0 million from operating activities in cash, contributing to free cash flow.

data.title: Warby Parker reports 13.0% revenue growth in 2025, with $324 per customer and 7.0% Active Customer growth.
data.description: Warby Parker Inc., a leading direct-to-consumer lifestyle brand specializing in vision products, revealed its financial performance for the fourth quarter and full year ending on December 31, 2025. Throughout the year, the company saw a revenue increase of 13.0%, with the fourth quarter specifically experiencing an 11.2% growth. The number of Active Customers grew by 7.0%, and the Average Revenue per Customer reached $324, marking a 5.7% increase compared to the previous year. Additionally, Warby Parker achieved its first year of positive net income.

data.title: Swiss spin-off Clee Medical, developing imaging tech for brain surgery, secures seed funding led by HTGF.
data.description: In Geneva, the Wyss Center for Bio and Neuroengineering revealed the completion of the Seed funding round for Clee Medical SA, a Swiss neurotech spin-off pioneering high-resolution real-time intraoperative imaging for brain surgeries. The financing, led by High-Tech Gründerfonds (HTGF), saw involvement from Zürcher Kantonalbank (ZKB), Kickfund, FONGIT, and Venture Kick alongside existing investor Wyss Center Geneva. Clee Medical, a spin-off from Wyss Center, achieved this milestone in their development.
